**CSS** works by selecting HTML elements and applying styles:

```css
/* Target all h1 tags */
h1 {
  color: #2d2d2d;
  font-size: 2rem;
}

/* Target elements with class='card' */
.card {
  background: white;
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 24px;
}

/* Target the element with id='hero' */
#hero {
  background: #4f46e5;
  color: white;
}
```

**Three selector types:**
- `tag` — targets all elements of that type
- `.class` — targets elements with that class (reusable)
- `#id` — targets one specific element (unique)

Classes are the most common. Use IDs sparingly.

**Colors:** Use hex (`#ff5733`), RGB (`rgb(255, 87, 51)`), or CSS variables (`var(--primary)`).

**Fonts:** Import from Google Fonts or use system fonts:
```css
body {
  font-family: 'Inter', -apple-system, sans-serif;
  font-size: 16px;
  line-height: 1.6;
}
```

**The Box Model** — every element is a box:
```css
.card {
  padding: 24px;    /* Space inside the border */
  margin: 16px;     /* Space outside the border */
  border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;
  border-radius: 8px;
  width: 320px;
}
```

Understanding padding vs. margin is one of the most important CSS concepts. Padding = inside. Margin = outside. When things look wrong, it's usually a padding/margin issue.

**Flexbox** is the easiest way to create flexible layouts:

```css
.nav {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between; /* space between items horizontally */
  align-items: center;           /* center vertically */
  gap: 16px;                    /* space between items */
}

.card-grid {
  display: flex;
  flex-wrap: wrap;   /* wrap to next line if no space */
  gap: 24px;
}

.card {
  flex: 1;           /* each card takes equal space */
  min-width: 280px;  /* but not smaller than this */
}
```

You need 5 properties: `display: flex`, `justify-content`, `align-items`, `gap`, `flex-wrap`.

Ask Claude: 'I need a 3-column card layout that stacks on mobile. Write the CSS using Flexbox.'

**DOM** stands for Document Object Model. The browser converts your HTML into a tree of JavaScript objects that you can manipulate.

```js
// Select elements
const title = document.querySelector('h1');
const button = document.querySelector('#submit-btn');
const cards = document.querySelectorAll('.card'); // returns all matches

// Read content
console.log(title.textContent); // 'Hello'

// Change content
title.textContent = 'Hello, Marcus!';

// Change styling
title.style.color = 'purple';

// Add/remove CSS classes
title.classList.add('active');
title.classList.remove('hidden');
title.classList.toggle('highlighted');
```

**Event listeners** let your code respond to user actions:

```js
const button = document.querySelector('#submit-btn');

button.addEventListener('click', () => {
  console.log('Button clicked!');
  button.textContent = 'Clicked!';
  button.disabled = true;
});

// Common events:
// 'click' — mouse click
// 'input' — text typed in a field
// 'submit' — form submitted
// 'keydown' — key pressed
// 'mouseover' — mouse hovers

// Input event example:
const searchInput = document.querySelector('#search');
searchInput.addEventListener('input', (event) => {
  console.log('User typed:', event.target.value);
});
```

Put it all together — a simple counter:

```html
<div id="app">
  <h2 id="count">0</h2>
  <button id="increment">+ Add</button>
  <button id="decrement">- Remove</button>
  <button id="reset">Reset</button>
</div>
```

```js
let count = 0;
const countDisplay = document.querySelector('#count');

const updateDisplay = () => {
  countDisplay.textContent = count;
  countDisplay.style.color = count < 0 ? 'red' : 'green';
};

document.querySelector('#increment').addEventListener('click', () => {
  count++;
  updateDisplay();
});

document.querySelector('#decrement').addEventListener('click', () => {
  count--;
  updateDisplay();
});

document.querySelector('#reset').addEventListener('click', () => {
  count = 0;
  updateDisplay();
});
```

This is a complete, working app. State (count) → event → update state → update display. That's the pattern behind every React app too.

By default, submitting a form *reloads the page* — you lose all your data. Prevent this:

```js
const form = document.querySelector('#signup-form');

form.addEventListener('submit', (event) => {
  event.preventDefault(); // STOP the page reload

  // Get values from form fields
  const name = document.querySelector('#name').value;
  const email = document.querySelector('#email').value;
  const plan = document.querySelector('#plan').value;

  console.log({ name, email, plan });

  // Validate
  if (!name.trim()) {
    alert('Please enter your name');
    return;
  }

  // Process: send to API, update UI, etc.
});
```

`event.preventDefault()` is the most important line in any form handler. Always start with it.

Validation catches errors before sending data to a server:

```js
const validateSignup = ({ name, email, password }) => {
  const errors = [];

  if (!name.trim()) {
    errors.push('Name is required');
  }

  if (!email.includes('@') || !email.includes('.')) {
    errors.push('Invalid email address');
  }

  if (password.length < 8) {
    errors.push('Password must be at least 8 characters');
  }

  return errors; // empty array = valid
};

// Usage:
const errors = validateSignup({ name, email, password });
if (errors.length > 0) {
  showErrors(errors); // display to user
  return;
}
// Proceed with valid data
```

Return an array of errors — you can show all of them at once rather than one at a time.
